# Architectural Boundary Rules

## Documentation Drives Implementation

Do not implement features that are not documented.

Implementation must follow:

* PROJECT.md
* docs/ARCHITECTURE.md
* docs/DECISIONS.md
* docs/plans/active/

---

## Agent Owns Conversation

Conversation history belongs to the LangGraph agent.

Knowledge documents belong to the knowledge layer.

Do not store retrieved document content as durable conversation state.

---

## MCP Owns Knowledge Access

All document operations must go through MCP.

Examples:

* search
* indexing
* document retrieval
* statistics

The agent must not bypass MCP.

---

## Retrieval Does Not Call LLM

The retrieval layer is deterministic.

Retrieval components must not call LLMs.

Examples:

* dense retrieval
* BM25 retrieval
* fusion
* reranking

must remain independent from model inference.

---

## Single LLM Boundary

All model calls go through:

```text
llm/
```

The LangGraph agent may use the LLM.

The MCP server must not call the LLM.

The retrieval layer must not call the LLM.

The storage layer must not call the LLM.

---

## LLM Context Is Not Durable Memory

Do not rely on the model context window as system memory.

Persist required state explicitly.

---

## Human Approval Required

Potentially destructive indexing operations require explicit user approval.

Examples:

* index rebuild
* reindexing
* index replacement

---

# Dependency Flow

Preferred:

```text
agent
    ↓
mcp_server
    ↓
retrieval
    ↓
storage
```

```text
agent
    ↓
llm
```

```text
indexing
    ↓
storage
```

Forbidden:

```text
mcp_server → llm
retrieval → llm
storage → llm
storage → agent
retrieval → agent
```

The retrieval layer is a service provider.

The agent is the orchestration layer.

---

# Documentation Consistency Rule

When documentation and implementation disagree:

1. Update documentation if the change is intentional.
2. Update implementation if documentation is authoritative.

Never leave the repository in an inconsistent state.
